From: Cristian <pcristian292@gmail.com>
Subject: [PATCH] en75_bmt + nanddev: bypass OOB-marker bad-block detection for UBI

Three coordinated fixes for the en75_bmt+spi-nand stack so UBI overlay
persistence works on devices like the TP-Link Archer XR500v (EN751221 +
GD5F1GQ4xA SPI-NAND):

1. en75_bmt overrides mtd->_block_isbad to always return 0 for in-range
   blocks. en75_bmt already shrinks mtd->size via the BBT shift, so any
   block reachable through the visible MTD is good by construction. The
   default chain (mtk_bmt_block_isbad -> spinand_mtd_block_isbad ->
   spinand_isbad) reads OOB[0..1] raw and mis-flags blocks whose OOB
   carries residue from prior writes.

2. en75_bmt overrides mtd->_block_markbad to a no-op. The default path
   stamps OOB[0..1] = 0x00 raw via spinand_markbad, which would persist
   false bad-block markers when UBI sees a transient read error and tries
   to mark a block bad. UBI's own per-PEB bad-block tracking (driven by
   CONFIG_MTD_UBI_BEB_LIMIT) handles wear-out without needing the OOB
   marker; the BMT (Block Mapping Table) en75_bmt manages handles real
   factory-bad blocks. So we don't need OOB markbad at all.

3. nanddev_erase in core.c is patched to skip the nanddev_isbad gate.
   Without this, mtk_bmt_mtd_erase -> spinand_mtd_erase -> nanddev_mtd_erase
   -> nanddev_erase rejects with -EIO any block whose raw OOB[0..1] looks
   bad. The override of mtd->_block_isbad doesn't help because nanddev_erase
   calls nanddev_isbad directly through nand->ops->isbad, not through
   mtd->_block_isbad. Skipping the isbad gate here is safe: if the block
   is truly unerasable, nand->ops->erase will fail with -EIO and the upper
   layer (UBI) handles it via its own bad-PEB tracking. nanddev_isreserved
   still applies, which is the legitimate "this region is off-limits" check.

Tested on TP-Link Archer XR500v: with this triple fix, ubiformat /dev/mtd7
succeeds on a contaminated NAND where it would otherwise fail with
"consecutive bad blocks exceed limit" after the first few PEBs.

--- a/drivers/mtd/nand/core.c
+++ b/drivers/mtd/nand/core.c
@@ -185,9 +185,15 @@ EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(nanddev_mtd_max_bad_blocks);
  */
 static int nanddev_erase(struct nand_device *nand, const struct nand_pos *pos)
 {
-	if (nanddev_isbad(nand, pos) || nanddev_isreserved(nand, pos)) {
-		pr_warn("attempt to erase a bad/reserved block @%llx\n",
-			nanddev_pos_to_offs(nand, pos));
+	/*
+	 * Don't gate on nanddev_isbad here: on stacks like mtk_bmt + spi-nand
+	 * + UBI, the raw OOB[0..1] read inside nanddev_isbad mis-flags blocks
+	 * whose OOB carries non-0xFF residue from prior writes, even though
+	 * the block itself is healthy. If the block is truly bad, the
+	 * underlying erase op will return -EIO and the caller can handle it.
+	 */
+	if (nanddev_isreserved(nand, pos)) {
+		pr_warn("attempt to erase a reserved block @%llx\n",
+			nanddev_pos_to_offs(nand, pos));
 		return -EIO;
 	}

--- a/drivers/mtd/nand/en75_bmt.c
+++ b/drivers/mtd/nand/en75_bmt.c
@@ -1361,12 +1361,42 @@ static int w_init(struct en75_bmt_m *ctx, struct device_node *np)

 static struct en75_bmt_m en75_bmt_m;

+/*
+ * UBI persistence depends on mtd_block_isbad() not lying about good blocks.
+ * The default chain mtk_bmt_block_isbad -> spinand_mtd_block_isbad reads
+ * OOB[0..1] raw and returns BAD for any non-0xFF, which mis-flags blocks
+ * whose OOB carries residue from prior writes, even though the block itself
+ * is healthy. en75_bmt has already excluded all factory-bad blocks from the
+ * visible MTD size via get_mapping_block_bbt()'s shift; any block reachable
+ * through the MTD is good by construction. So return 0 unconditionally.
+ * UBI's own per-PEB tracking (CONFIG_MTD_UBI_BEB_LIMIT) handles runtime
+ * wear-out without needing the OOB-based discriminator.
+ */
+static int en75_block_isbad(struct mtd_info *mtd, loff_t ofs)
+{
+	if (ofs < 0 || ofs >= mtd->size)
+		return 1;
+	return 0;
+}
+
+/*
+ * Suppress mtd_block_markbad: the default chain stamps OOB[0..1] = 0x00
+ * raw via spinand_markbad, which would persist false bad markers if UBI
+ * (or any upper layer) calls markbad on a block that's actually healthy.
+ * Real factory-bad blocks are tracked by the BMT/BBT en75_bmt manages;
+ * runtime bad-PEB management is UBI's own concern.
+ */
+static int en75_block_markbad(struct mtd_info *mtd, loff_t ofs)
+{
+	return 0;
+}
+
 static int pub_init(struct device_node *np)
 {
 	int ret;

 	ret = w_init(&en75_bmt_m, np);
-	if (!ret)
+	if (!ret) {
 		w_sync_tables(&en75_bmt_m);
+		en75_bmt_m.mtk->mtd->_block_isbad = en75_block_isbad;
+		en75_bmt_m.mtk->mtd->_block_markbad = en75_block_markbad;
+	}
 	return ret;
 }

